{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Architecture · Stisla{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Architecture</h1>
    <p class="lead">How customization works in practice. Worked examples for the override paths, state derivation, and when to write a real component.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>Why this page exists</h2>
    <p>The <a class="link" href="/specification">Specification</a> page tells you what every implementation agrees on, and the <a class="link" href="/customization">Customization</a> page lists the tokens you can change. This page walks through how the pieces actually fit together when you sit down to make a change. Same examples you would build at work. Same questions you would ask.</p>
    <p>The thesis is small. Scoped CSS variables plus BEM plus cascade order behave like CSS Modules without a build step. You don&rsquo;t need specificity wars and you don&rsquo;t need <code>!important</code> outside utilities. The rest of this page is concrete examples that show why.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The token surface</h2>
    <p>Every Stisla component reads from a small set of <code>--st-*</code> custom properties. They live on <code>:root</code> and flip selectively on <code>[data-theme="dark"]</code>. Every background-providing token has a paired <code>-foreground</code> so contrast survives an override. State variants (hover, active, focus) derive at runtime through <code>color-mix(in oklch, &hellip;)</code>, which means changing one token repaints every state. The full set is on the <a class="link" href="/customization">Customization</a> page. Everything below assumes that surface.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Override scopes</h2>
    <p>The cascade gives you four scopes for any override. Same mechanism (CSS variable plus inheritance) at every level. Specificity never fights you because variables inherit; selectors don&rsquo;t.</p>
    <p>The scenario is the same in each example: turn the primary brand color green. Pick the smallest scope that covers what you actually need.</p>

    <h3>Global</h3>
    <p>The change applies to the whole app. Drop this in a stylesheet that loads after <code>stisla.css</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
:root {
  --st-primary: oklch(0.65 0.18 149);
}
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Theme variant</h3>
    <p>Same write, scoped to a theme attribute. Toggle <code>data-theme="brand"</code> on <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> (or any wrapper) to switch in.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
[data-theme="brand"] {
  --st-primary: oklch(0.65 0.18 149);
}
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Scoped wrapper</h3>
    <p>Only the dashboard subtree retints. Every <code>.btn--primary</code>, every primary-tinted alert or badge inside <code>.dashboard</code> picks up the green automatically because the variable inherits down the tree.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
.dashboard {
  --st-primary: oklch(0.65 0.18 149);
}
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Single element</h3>
    <p>One element, one override. Inline styles always win on specificity, so you don&rsquo;t need <code>!important</code> and you don&rsquo;t need a class.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<button class="btn btn--primary" style="--st-primary: oklch(0.65 0.18 149)">
  Save
</button>
    {% endcall %}

    <p>Pick the smallest scope that still covers what you need to change. A one-off brand button doesn&rsquo;t need a global retheme. A multi-section dashboard doesn&rsquo;t need an inline write on every element.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Tweak one part of a component</h2>
    <p>The everyday case looks like this. You like the button, you just want the icon a bit larger. Three escalation levels, from least invasive to most. Stop at the one that matches how broad the change really is.</p>

    <h3>Option A. Inline override of the component variable</h3>
    <p>Bumps the icon size inside this one button. <code>--btn-icon-size</code> defaults to <code>1em</code> on every <code>.btn</code>; setting it inline only affects this element. Tone, padding, height all stay default.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<button class="btn btn--primary" style="--btn-icon-size: 1.25em">
  <i data-lucide="upload"></i>
  Upload
</button>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Option B. Your own scoped class</h3>
    <p>You want the icon-prominent treatment in more than one place. Write a modifier class once, apply it where you want it. The variable inherits down to the icon rules from Stisla&rsquo;s base.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css', title='app.css') %}
.btn--prominent-icon {
  --btn-icon-size: 1.25em;
}
    {% endcall %}
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<button class="btn btn--primary btn--prominent-icon">
  <i data-lucide="upload"></i>
  Upload
</button>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Specificity matches Stisla&rsquo;s own rule (one class). Your stylesheet loads after <code>stisla.css</code>, so cascade order resolves it. No <code>!important</code>.</p>

    <h3>Option C. Wrap a region</h3>
    <p>Every button inside a region gets the bigger icon. Useful for toolbars and command bars where the icon is the dominant read.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css', title='app.css') %}
.toolbar .btn {
  --btn-icon-size: 1.25em;
}
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Higher specificity (two classes beat one), so this wins even if your stylesheet loads before Stisla&rsquo;s. Use it when you can&rsquo;t control load order, or when the change really belongs to a region rather than a button modifier.</p>

    <p>Where your custom CSS lives is a separate question from these three options. App-wide overrides go in one <code>app.css</code> (or equivalent) loaded after <code>stisla.css</code>. Component-style classes co-locate with the component when you&rsquo;re inside a framework. Per-page overrides go in a per-page stylesheet, or a wrapper class on the page root. The principle is the same as the scope ladder above. Don&rsquo;t reach wider than you need to.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Tweak something that has no variable</h2>
    <p>Plenty of properties in Stisla aren&rsquo;t exposed as variables, and that&rsquo;s deliberate (see <a class="link" href="#what-to-expose">What to expose</a> below). You still have a clean path. Same three escalation options as the icon-size walk, only now you&rsquo;re targeting the property directly.</p>
    <p>Scenario: the gap between icon and label inside <code>.btn</code> is hardcoded to <code>0.5rem</code>. No <code>--btn-gap</code> variable exists. You want it tighter.</p>

    <h3>Option A. Inline style</h3>
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<button class="btn btn--primary" style="gap: 0.25rem">
  <i data-lucide="check"></i>
  Save
</button>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Inline always wins. No specificity battle.</p>

    <h3>Option B. Your own scoped class</h3>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css', title='app.css') %}
.btn--tight { gap: 0.25rem; }
    {% endcall %}
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<button class="btn btn--primary btn--tight">
  <i data-lucide="check"></i>
  Save
</button>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Same specificity as Stisla&rsquo;s <code>.btn</code> rule (one class). Your stylesheet loads after, so cascade order resolves it.</p>

    <h3>Option C. Region-scoped</h3>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css', title='app.css') %}
.toolbar .btn { gap: 0.25rem; }
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Two classes beat one. Wins regardless of load order.</p>

    <p>The takeaway: a missing variable doesn&rsquo;t block you. The cascade and specificity rules give you a clean override path even when there&rsquo;s nothing scoped to override.</p>
    <p>There&rsquo;s a feedback loop here. If you find yourself overriding the same property in three or more places (one specific <code>gap</code>, one specific <code>padding</code>, one specific <code>font-weight</code>), that&rsquo;s the signal it should become a Stisla variable. File an issue. The user-side overrides are the input to the public knob surface. That&rsquo;s how <code>--btn-rim-mix</code> got exposed when <code>.btn-group</code> needed to lift it.</p>
    <p>Skip the issue when your override is genuinely one-off, project-specific, or just personal preference. Leave those on the project side. Variables are for shared, recurring tunes.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>State derivation and escape hatches</h2>
    <p>Stisla derives hover, active, and focus colors from a single source via <code>color-mix(in oklch, &hellip;)</code>. Change one variable and every state recomputes. This is the easy path. It&rsquo;s also escapable at three levels when you want hand-tuned states.</p>
    <p>The reference is <code>.btn</code>. The same pattern shows up in alert, badge, dialog, kbd, list-group, scroll-area, table, and a dozen other components.</p>

    <h3>Level 1. Keep color-mix, swap the source</h3>
    <p>You like the curve, you want a different brand color. Set <code>--btn-tone</code> and let everything else derive from it.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<button class="btn" style="--btn-tone: oklch(0.6 0.2 30)">Brand</button>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Hover, active, rim, and bevel all recompute through the same recipe (hover at 88%, active at 78%, rim at 85%). One write, the full state machinery stays intact. Reach for this when only the base color changes.</p>

    <h3>Level 2. Keep the variable surface, bypass color-mix per state</h3>
    <p>You want hand-picked swatches at each state instead of the derived progression. Set each state&rsquo;s background directly. <code>color-mix</code> never runs because you&rsquo;re writing the final value.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
.btn--brand        { --btn-bg: oklch(0.60 0.22 30); }
.btn--brand:hover  { --btn-bg: oklch(0.55 0.22 30); }
.btn--brand:active { --btn-bg: oklch(0.50 0.24 30); }
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Use when the auto-derived progression doesn&rsquo;t match a designer&rsquo;s hand-picked swatch, or when the perceptual ramp isn&rsquo;t right for an unusual hue.</p>

    <h3>Level 3. Skip the variable layer entirely</h3>
    <p>Plain CSS. Cascade and specificity resolve it. The variable layer isn&rsquo;t involved at all.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
.my-cta        { background: red; }
.my-cta:hover  { background: darkred; }
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Use when you&rsquo;re styling something that doesn&rsquo;t belong in Stisla&rsquo;s tone model. A designer-supplied gradient CTA, for instance.</p>

    <p>Here&rsquo;s the framing behind these three. Most design systems pick one mode (forced derivation, or fully manual). Stisla offers both, and you pick per situation. The level you reach for is the level you need. Don&rsquo;t over-commit. Level 1 for a color change, Level 2 for a curve change, Level 3 for leaving the system.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Building your own component</h2>
    <p>The teaching frame is the rule of three. Don&rsquo;t abstract until you&rsquo;ve used the same pattern three times. Two uses is duplication. Three is a pattern.</p>

    <h3>First use, second use, third use</h3>
    <p><strong>First use.</strong> Name it specifically. A card showing a product is <code>product-card</code>. Reach for the specific name over a generic guess like <code>media-card</code> or <code>card-with-image</code>. Specific names are honest, and renaming later is cheaper than un-abstracting.</p>
    <p><strong>Second use, same structure, different content.</strong> You have <code>product-card</code> and now need <code>article-card</code>. Look at what&rsquo;s actually shared.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Same DOM, same visual treatment.</strong> Rename to a content-neutral name that describes structure (<code>media-card</code>), or use the existing <code>.card</code> with a <code>.card__media</code> part. One class, two uses.</li>
      <li><strong>Same visual treatment, different DOM.</strong> Write a small Sass placeholder or mixin (<code>@mixin elevated-surface</code>) and include it in both. Two classes, one source of truth for the shared bit.</li>
      <li><strong>Looks similar but actually diverges.</strong> Duplicate. Premature unification costs more than duplication; you&rsquo;ll regret it the first time one of them needs to evolve independently.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Third use.</strong> Now you have permission to abstract. The shape of the abstraction reveals itself by then. The class names, the variables, the parts. They&rsquo;re obvious because you&rsquo;ve already written them three times.</p>

    <h3>Worked example: <code>.notice</code></h3>
    <p>A short banner with an icon, a message, and an intent. Thirty-ish lines of Sass using Stisla patterns end to end.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss', title='src/scss/components/_notice.scss') %}
.notice {
  // Component-scoped vars. Each one falls back through a global token so
  // the global density / radius / surface knobs reach this component.
  --notice-padding: calc(0.75rem * var(--st-density));
  --notice-radius:  var(--st-radius);
  --notice-gap:     0.5rem;

  // Tone is the single source. bg / color / border derive from it via
  // color-mix, so swapping --notice-tone repaints every part.
  --notice-tone:    var(--st-foreground);
  --notice-bg:      color-mix(in oklch, var(--notice-tone) 10%, var(--st-surface));
  --notice-color:   var(--notice-tone);
  --notice-border:  color-mix(in oklch, var(--notice-tone) 25%, transparent);

  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: var(--notice-gap);
  padding: var(--notice-padding);

  background: var(--notice-bg);
  color: var(--notice-color);
  border: 1px solid var(--notice-border);
  border-radius: var(--notice-radius);
}

// Intent modifiers — reassign the source. Every derived var follows.
.notice--info    { --notice-tone: var(--st-info); }
.notice--success { --notice-tone: var(--st-success); }
.notice--warning { --notice-tone: var(--st-warning); }
.notice--danger  { --notice-tone: var(--st-danger); }
    {% endcall %}
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<div class="notice notice--info">
  <i data-lucide="info"></i>
  <span>Saved 2 minutes ago.</span>
</div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The component composes with the rest of the system for free. Put a <code>.btn</code> inside one, and the button still reads from <code>--st-primary</code> as expected. Override <code>--st-info</code> on a parent and the info-toned notice repaints. Override <code>--notice-tone</code> inline for a one-off and you get the same machinery without authoring a new modifier.</p>
    <p>Document the component the same way every Stisla component is documented. A Customization table at the end of the page listing the <code>--notice-*</code> variables (Variable, Default, Use). The <a class="link" href="/slider#customization">Slider</a> page is the reference shape.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="what-to-expose">
    <h2>What to expose, what to hardcode</h2>
    <p>It&rsquo;s tempting to expose every value as a variable, but the cost shows up later. A bloated public API turns every internal tweak into a breaking change, gives users decision fatigue (which knob do I use?), and adds a documentation burden (every var needs a row in the Customization table).</p>

    <h3>Expose a CSS variable when</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>The value is something a designer would tune per project (color, radius, density, type scale).</li>
      <li>The value is a meaningful per-instance override (button tone, dialog width, icon size for an icon-prominent UI).</li>
      <li>Multiple components share the same recipe (focus ring color, overlay scrim).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Don&rsquo;t expose a CSS variable when</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>The value is internal tuning. State-derivation percentages (the 88% / 78% in the button hover/active mix) are part of the recipe. Exposing them as knobs would let users break the visual progression by accident.</li>
      <li>The value only makes sense to change as a pair with other internal values.</li>
      <li>You can&rsquo;t articulate a use case for changing it.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Easier to add a variable later than to remove one. Start conservative. The user override patterns are the right input to what becomes public.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why you don&rsquo;t need <code>!important</code></h2>
    <p>With scoped variables plus BEM plus cascade order, you can override anything in Stisla without <code>!important</code>. Four common scenarios.</p>

    <h3>Change a token globally</h3>
    <p>Set <code>--st-primary</code> in your own stylesheet loaded after Stisla. Wins because cascade order resolves it. No specificity fight because nothing in Stisla defines <code>--st-primary</code> outside <code>:root</code>.</p>

    <h3>Override a component property on a single element</h3>
    <p>Inline style on the element. Wins because inline-style specificity beats any class. No <code>!important</code>.</p>

    <h3>Override a component property in a region</h3>
    <p>Wrapper class plus the same selector. Specificity ties on the inner rule, and load order breaks the tie in your favor. Or bump specificity by one with <code>.region .btn { &hellip; }</code>.</p>

    <h3>Override a component variable for a region</h3>
    <p>Set the variable on the wrapper. Every descendant <code>.btn</code> inherits it. No fight at all because variables inherit. The cascade isn&rsquo;t even involved in the <em>use</em> of the variable, only in the <em>definition</em>.</p>

    <h3>The one exception: utilities</h3>
    <p>Utility classes (everything in <a class="link" href="/utilities">/utilities</a>) ship with <code>!important</code> on purpose. A utility is a tweak meant to win. If <code>.text-primary</code> is on an element, the user is explicitly saying &ldquo;this color, no matter what.&rdquo; The <code>!important</code> makes that promise reliable. This is the one place <code>!important</code> is appropriate.</p>
    <p>The general rule reads like this. <code>!important</code> in component CSS is a smell. <code>!important</code> in utility CSS is a contract.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to use a utility, when to write a component</h2>
    <p>The utilities file header puts it as a rule. Utilities are tweaks. They aren&rsquo;t building blocks. If you reach for the same utility chain three times, write a component. If you reach for it once or twice, leave it inline.</p>
    <p>The concrete signal is utility-stacking. Putting <code>.d-flex .gap-3 .p-4 .rounded .border</code> on a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> to build something card-shaped means you&rsquo;re using utilities as building blocks. Write the component instead. The component file is small, scoped, deletable, and tells the next reader of the code what the thing actually is.</p>
    <p>The handful of utilities Stisla ships exist for the small set of tweaks that genuinely don&rsquo;t need a component. A heading muted in one place. A button row with extra gap to its neighbor. A card that needs to be flex in a single layout. That&rsquo;s the entire purpose.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What&rsquo;s next</h2>
    <p>Browse the <a class="link" href="/customization">Customization</a> page for the full token table and the preset recipes (brutalist, dense, brand swap). Read <a class="link" href="/comparisons">Comparisons</a> for how Stisla sits next to Tailwind, Bootstrap, and shadcn. Or open any component page to see the per-component Customization table that documents its <code>--component-*</code> surface.</p>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
